# Direct Syntax — `direct[M] { ... }` do-notation

Exercises the v1.8 direct-syntax desugaring: monadic bind (`x = expr`),
pure val binding (`val x = expr`), bind-and-discard (`val _ = expr`),
mutable vars, and nested blocks.

## Option — happy path

```scalascript
val r1 = direct[Option] {
  x = Some(40)
  y = Some(2)
  Some(x + y)
}
println(r1)
```

## Option — short-circuit on None

```scalascript
val r2 = direct[Option] {
  x = Some(1)
  y = None
  Some(x + y)
}
println(r2)
```

## Pure val binding inside direct block

```scalascript
val r3 = direct[Option] {
  x = Some(10)
  val doubled = x * 2
  Some(doubled)
}
println(r3)
```

## Bind-and-discard (`val _ = expr`)

```scalascript
val r4 = direct[Option] {
  val _ = Some("logged")
  x = Some(42)
  Some(x)
}
println(r4)
```

## Mutable var inside direct block

```scalascript
val r5 = direct[Option] {
  var counter = 0
  x = Some(10)
  counter = counter + x
  Some(counter)
}
println(r5)
```

## List — Cartesian product

```scalascript
val r6 = direct[List] {
  x = List(1, 2)
  y = List(10, 20)
  List(x + y)
}
println(r6)
```

## Nested direct blocks

```scalascript
val inner = direct[Option] {
  a = Some(3)
  Some(a + 1)
}
val outer = direct[Option] {
  x = inner
  Some(x * 10)
}
println(outer)
```

## Three-bind chain

```scalascript
val r8 = direct[Option] {
  a = Some(1)
  b = Some(2)
  c = Some(3)
  Some(a + b + c)
}
println(r8)
```
